# VIM Advance Operations   --- 
## Types of Modes in Vim Editor 
 **Insert Mode** → Used to insert text into any file.   
 **ESC Mode** → Used to perform different operations (copy, paste, delete, undo, redo, etc.).   
 **Command or Colon Mode** → Used to run commands.   
**Example:**   
`:wq` → Save and quit   --- 
## Vi and Vim Advance Operations 
```bash 
# cp /etc/passwd /root 
# ls 
# vim passwd 
``` --- 
### Examples of Insert Mode 
- `i` → Insert text **before** the cursor   - `a` → Insert text **after** the cursor   - `o` → Insert new line **below** the cursor   - `Shift + o` → Insert new line **above** the cursor   --- 
### Examples of ESC Mode - `yy` → Copy one line (`nyy` to copy *n* lines)   - `p` → Paste content   - `dd` → Delete one line   - `u` → Undo   - `Ctrl + r` → Redo   - `cc` → Cut & copy a line   - `yw` → Copy a word   - `dw` → Delete a word   - `cw` → Cut & copy a word   - `Shift + d` → Delete from cursor to end of line   - `x` → Delete character (forward)   - `Shift + x` → Delete character (backward)   - `Shift + g` → Go to end of file   - `gg` → Go to start of file   - `0` → Go to beginning of line   - `Shift + $` → Go to end of line   
- `b` → Move cursor **word by word backward**   - `w` → Move cursor **word by word forward**   - `/root` → Search a word (Press `n` for next, `Shift + n` for previous)   --- 
### Examples of Command / Colon Mode - `:set number` OR `:se nu` → Show line numbers   - `:10` → Jump to line number 10   - `:se nonu` → Remove line numbers   - `:se ic` → Disable case sensitivity   - `/ROOT` → Search without case sensitivity   - `:se noic` → Enable case sensitivity again   - `:nohl` → Remove highlighted search results   - `:wq` OR `:x` → Save and quit   - `:q!` → Quit without saving   --- 
## Copy Lines from One File to Another 
```bash 
# vim passwd 
5yy       
# Copy 5 lines 
:edit /report 
p         
# Paste content 
:wq       
# Save & quit 
# cat /report 
``` --- 
## Set Permanent Line Numbers in All Files 
```bash 
# vim ~/.vimrc 
se nu 
:wq 
``` 
Now, line numbers will appear automatically in every file.   --- 
## Search and Replace in Vim 
```bash 
# vim passwd 
:%s/root/network/g       
# Replace all "root" with "network" 
:1s/network/root/g       
# Replace only in line 1 
:1,13s/network/root/gi   # Replace from line 1 to 13 (ignore case) 
:%s/nologin/bash/gic     # Confirm before replace 
:wq                      
``` --- 
# Save & quit 
## Using `sed` Command (Stream Editor) 
```bash 
lsblk | grep part | sed 's/part/partitions/' 
lsblk | grep part | sed 's/part/partitions/g' 
lsblk | sed -e 's/boot/booting/g' -e 's/SWAP/swap/g' 
lsblk | sed 's/boot/booting/g;s/SWAP/swap/g' 
``` 
### Replace in a File with `sed` 
```bash 
head /etc/passwd > /report 
cat /report 
sed 's/root/japan/g' /report        
# Replace but not save 
sed -i 's/root/japan/g' /report     # Replace & save permanently 
sed -i 's/japan/root/g' /report     # Replace back 
sed 's/root/japan/2' /report        
# Replace 2nd occurrence only 
sed '1,5s/root/japan/g' /report     # Replace from line 1 to 5 
sed -i '1,5s/root/japan/g' /report  # Replace from 1 to 5 & save 
sed -i '1,5s/root/japan/gi' /report # Replace ignoring case 
``` 
**Example Output:** 
``` 
japan:x:0:0:japan:/japan:/bin/bash 
bin:x:1:1:bin:/bin:/sbin/nologin 
daemon:x:2:2:daemon:/sbin:/sbin/nologin
